name: Quercus douglasii Hook. & Arn.
recordedBy: LeRoy Gross; Pam DeVries, Melinda Elster
habitat: Trail started along road on ridgeline of chaparral, then down sunny thick chaparral slope to a narrow rift valley with heavy soil. Grassy valley dominated with oaks. Mostly Quercus douglasii, then smaller amounts of Q. agrifolia, Q. lobata. Leave valley for more chaparral. Then close to the end some more grassy area with oaks. Growing in valley.
locality: East end of the Santa Lucia Wilderness. Started at locked gate to lookout on Hi Mountain, then south southeast to Hi Valley, then east to Road 30S05.2.; Santa Margarita Lake, Tar Spring Ridge 7.5'Trail started near 35.26052N 120.42981W. ended at 35.24926N 120.38324W. T31S R15E S8 NE1/4.
associatedTaxa: Chaparral had components of: Adenostoma fasciculatum, Quercus berberidifolia, Garrya veatchii, G. flavescens, Eriodictyon tomentosum, Arctostaphylos glandulosa, A. glauca, Trichostema lanatum, Pickeringia montana, Ceanothus cuneatus, C. oliganthus, Galium andrewsii, G. porrigens, Eriogonum fasciculatum, E. elongatum, Rhamnus ilicifolia, Salvia mellifera, Linanthus californicus, Dendromecon rigida, Heteromeles arbutifolia, Prunus ilicifolia, and Cercocarpus betuloides. Valley had components of: Toxicodendron diversilobum, Ranunculus californicus, Viola pedunculata, Sanicula crassicaulis, S. bipinnata, S. bipinnatifida, Lomatium utriculatum, Plectritis ciliosa, Sisyrinchium bellum, Bromus diandrus, Melica californica, and Hordeum brachyantherum californicum.

name: Quercus douglasii Hook. & Arn.
occurrenceRemarks: On slope near chaparral; Forming clumps
habitat: Open grassy slopes and foothill woodland with rock outcrops, grading into woodland chaparral on north-facing exposures. Foothill woodland with Quercus agrifolia, Q. lobata, and Q. douglasii as dominant trees. Chaparral with Cercocarpus betuloides, Q. berberidifolia, and occasional Rhamnus ilicifolia as dominants
locality: Santa Rita Ranch Preserve, managed by Land Conservancy of San Luis Obispo County. South of California Route 46 and east of Old Creek Road in Santa Lucia Mountains. Slopes near northern preserve boundary south of Highway 46.
